text.tspan: Made for the Qiskit Community Summer Jam
Like all quantum gates, applying the X gate twice in a row brings the qubit back to its
original state. In fact, this property is the only requirement that quantum gates must
have! Try using more than one X gate on the same wire.
We now introduce a new gate: the Hadamard, or H gate. This is a very interesting gate
that puts the qubits between the and states. That is, you don't know what the qubit

tspan.tspan: will be until you measure it. Try to guess the pattern with the new states!

text.tspan: If we put multiple qubits into superposition, then the number of possible output states
(combinations of classical 0s and 1s) grows very quickly. This is, in part, what makes
quantum computing powerful. Let's try a harder pattern.
Let's introduce another gate: the Z gate. The effects of the Z gate are a little more
difficult to see, but can you figure it out? (Hint: the Z gate flips the sign of the qubits
The most basic of all the quantum gates is the X gate. It takes qubits from the state
to the state (or any rotation around the Bloch sphere). The Bloch sphere allows us
to see how our quantum gates affect the qubits we apply them to.
Drag the gates from the gate library to any of the
four wires to make a quantum circuit.
